Dear gentlman,

I would need your help in order to understand the following behavior of C++ code produced by Verilator.

I have to describe in Verilog this simple circuit:
!FF2.png!

Verilog code I have written is:

```
module Top( 
     input clock_i,
     input [31:0] data_i,

     output [31:0] data_o,
     output [31:0] data_delayed_o);    

     reg [31:0] data_o;
     reg [31:0] data_delayed_o;


     always @(posedge clock_i)
     begin
         data_delayed_o <= data_o;
     end 

     assign data_o = data_i;

endmodule

```

I have connected to C++ with:

```
VTop *top;

int main(int argc, char** argv, char** env){

	for(time = 0; time < 10; time++)
	{
		top->clock_i = (time == 0) ? 0 : !top->clock_i;
		if ( ((time % 2) != 0) && (time > 2))
		{
			top->addr_i = 0xA0 + time;
		}
		top->eval();
		// Read outputs
	}
	// Print signals
	top->final();
}

```

It works well: I get what I have expected that is *data_delayed_o* signal is delayed of one clock period respect to *data_i* signal as shown in figure below. But if I remove *data_o* signal from module output list I will not get the delay, but *data_i* and *data_delayed_o* are exactly the same.

Please, have you some suggestions about how I can remove *data_o* signal from output list without getting the error?

Thanks in advanced

Roberto

